Bootloader is the first software program that runs when a computer starts, acting as a bridge between firmware (BIOS/UEFI) and the operating system kernel. It loads the Linux kernel into memory, allows users to choose between multiple operating systems, and manages boot parameters to initiate the system. 

Function: It is responsible for transferring control from the hardware to the operating system.
GRUB2: The Grand Unified Bootloader (GRUB) is the most common, versatile, and default bootloader on most modern Linux distributions.
Alternatives: Other bootloaders include systemd-boot, rEFInd, and older options like LILO or SYSLINUX.
Dual Booting: When multiple operating systems are installed, the bootloader provides a menu to select which one to boot.
Process: After the BIOS/UEFI initializes hardware, it locates the bootloader (often in the Master Boot Record or an EFI partition) to start the booting process. 

How to Identify Your Bootloader:
You can use the efibootmgr program to check the "BootCurrent" option to see which bootloader is active on UEFI systems. 

Bootloader List

GRUB
Legacy BIOS Support=Yes
UEFI Support=Yes
Supports RAID, LUKS (but not Argon2 PBKDFs) and LVM (but not thin provisioned volumes). See GRUB for setup-specific limitations. 

systemd-boot
Legacy BIOS Support=No
UEFI Support=Yes
Can only launch binaries from the ESP it is installed to or from the Extended Boot Loader Partition (XBOOTLDR partition) on the same disk.
Automatically detects unified kernel images placed in esp/EFI/Linux/. 

Syslinux
Legacy BIOS Support=Yes
UEFI Support=Poor
No support for certain file system features.
Can only access the file system it was installed to. 

rEFInd
Legacy BIOS Support=No
UEFI Support=Yes
Supports auto-detecting kernels and parameters without explicit configuration, and supports fastboot 

Efistub
Legacy BIOS Support=No
UEFI Support=Yes
The kernel is a valid EFI executable which can be directly launched from UEFI or from another UEFI boot loader.

Limine
Legacy BIOS Support=Yes
UEFI Support=Yes
Supports GPT and MBR partitioning.
Can boot Linux, BSD, and other kernels Actively maintained, unlike LILO or Syslinux Lightweight design but modern enough to handle mixed setups.

LILO
Legacy BIOS Support=Yes
UEFI Support=No
Discontinued due to limitations (e.g. with Btrfs, GPT, RAID, encryption).

Windows Boot Manager
Legacy BIOS Support=Yes
UEFI Support=Yes
Windows Boot Manager does not natively or officially support loading Linux operating systems
as it is designed solely for Windows partitions. However, it is possible to configure Windows Boot Manager to chainload a Linux bootloader (like GRUB) to enable dual-booting, though it is not the standard or recommended approach.

Unified kernel image
Legacy BIOS Support=No
UEFI Support=Yes
systemd-stub(7), a kernel, initramfs and kernel command line packed into EFI executable to be loaded directly from UEFI firmware or another boot loader.

Clover
Legacy BIOS Support=Yes
UEFI Support=Yes
Can emulate UEFI on legacy BIOS systems.

GRUB Legacy
Legacy BIOS Support=Yes
UEFI Support=No
Discontinued in favor of GRUB.
